            <outline text="HaaS Outline">
                <outline text="The HaaS Concept #slide #">
                    <outline text="The concept of Human as a Sensor (HaaS) has known an explosive growth in the past years where the social network make observations about the physical world rather than automated sensor systems known as Internet of Things (IoT). HaaS is typically used to gather information regarding physical hazards,crimes and evolving emergencies so to enhance situational awarness and give an interseting reliable sensing problem."/>
                </outline>
                <outline text="Main Idea ?? #slide ">
                    <outline text="The observation made by HaaS prompts the question about its trustworthiness. In fact, these observation may be true or false, and hence are viewed as binary claims. As you might expect, this technology is not without its cybersecurity threats. Thus, the main idea lies in developping a model that consider the exact ways in which cybercriminals can manipulate HaaS, and how law enforcement can ensure that it gets credible real-time information. "/>
                </outline>
                <outline text="Difference between IoT and HaaS attacks ??"/>
                <outline text="Introduction to bayesian game:">
                    <outline text="Sometimes, players may have private information about their own payoffs,about their type or preferences.... This situation of asymmetric or incomplete infomation make the game a bayesian one.  In game theory, bayesian game is defined as a game in which each player have incomplete information on the other players (their available payoffs)  , but they have beliefs on probability distribution.  The way to modelling this situation incomplete information is by recurring toan idea generatedby Harsanyi (1967). The key is to introduce a move by the Nature, which transforms the uncertainty by converting an incomplete information problem into an imperfect information problem.The idea is the Nature moves determining playersí types, a concept thatembodies all the relevant private information about them (such as payoffs, preferences, beliefs about other players, etc)"/>
                    <outline text="Elements of the bayesian game :">
                        <outline text="Players $$i \in \{ 1,2,\ldots ,N\}$$">
                            <outline text="Finite type set for each player $$\theta_i \in \Theta_i$$"/>
                            <outline text=" probability distribution over types $$p(\theta)$$(common prior beliefs about the players' types)"/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="Finite action set for each player $$a_i \in A_i$$"/>
                        <outline text="Utilities :  $$u_i :A_1 \times A_2 \times \ldots A_N \times \theta_1 \times \theta_2 \times \ldots \theta_N \rightarrow \Re$$"/>
                    </outline>
                    <outline text="Bayesian Nash equilibrium :">
                        <outline text="A BNE is a set of strategies, one for each type of player, such that no type has icentive to change his or her strategy given the beliefs about the types and what the others types are doing.">
                            <outline text="BNE are more compilcated than NE because we need to find strategies for each type."/>
                            <outline text="Suprisingly, we can still use NE to find BNE for strategic form games. "/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="fa"/>
                    </outline>
                </outline>
